An '''open problem''' is a problem that can be formally stated and for which a solution is known to exist but which has not yet been solved. It is common in [[graduate school]]s to point out open problems to students. These students as well as [[Faculty (university)|faculty]] members engaged in research attempt to solve such problems. Recent examples of closed, or solved, problems by faculty members are [[Fermat's last theorem]] and the [[Four color theorem]].

Important open problems exist in many fields, such as in the field of theoretical computer science, computer scheduling, real-time computing, physics and mathematics.

